Looking at this code, I need to analyze the `computeMillis` method and determine which test cases actually trigger bugs in it.

The key issue in the buggy code is in this section:

```java
if (count > 0) {
    // alter base year for parsing if first field is month or day
    DurationField months = DurationFieldType.months().getField(iChrono);
    DurationField days = DurationFieldType.days().getField(iChrono);
    DurationField first = savedFields[0].iField.getDurationField();
    if (compareReverse(first, months) >= 0 && compareReverse(first, days) <= 0) {
        saveField(DateTimeFieldType.year(), iDefaultYear);
        return computeMillis(resetFields, text);  // RECURSIVE CALL
    }
}
```

This recursive call can cause infinite recursion if the saved fields aren't properly managed. The problem is that when `saveField` is called and then `computeMillis` is called recursively, if `iSavedFieldsShared` is true, the fields will be cloned again, but the newly saved year field might trigger the same condition again.

The fix requires ensuring that when we recurse, we don't keep adding the year field repeatedly. The proper fix is to set `iSavedFieldsShared = false` BEFORE the recursive call or to ensure the saved fields are properly managed.

